            <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl mb-6">
                INVESTIGATING THE ROLE OF AI AND HUMAN ACROSS RECRUITMENT STAGES: A CASE STUDY IN MALAYSIA [cite: 10]
            </h1>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 mb-8">EIB20503 Business Research Methods [cite: 7, 8]</p>
        </div>
    </header>

    <main class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12 space-y-16">

        <section id="abstract" class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-8 border border-gray-100">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4 border-b pb-2">Abstract</h2>
            <p class="mb-4">Artificial Intelligence (AI) is increasingly transforming recruitment by improving efficiency, speed, and data processing[cite: 20]. However, the roles of AI-based and human-based methods across specific recruitment stages remain unclear, especially in Malaysia[cite: 21].</p>
            <p class="mb-4">This study investigates the roles of these methods by measuring their involvement across six key recruitment stages: identifying needs/job analysis, sourcing and attraction, screening and shortlisting, assessment, interview, and induction/onboarding[cite: 24]. Data will be collected from at least 100 HR practitioners using a quantitative, cross-sectional design[cite: 25, 26]. The findings are expected to provide practical guidance for Malaysian organizations to allocate AI and human involvement more systematically[cite: 29].</p>
        </section>

        <section id="introduction" class="space-y-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-8 border border-gray-100">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4 border-b pb-2">Problem Statement</h2>
                <p>Even though AI is increasingly used in recruitment, existing studies provide limited explanation of how AI-based and human-based methods should be applied across specific recruitment stages[cite: 60, 63]. Without clear guidance, organizations may overuse AI in stages requiring human judgment or underuse it where automation could improve efficiency[cite: 67].</p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-8 border border-gray-100">
                    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4 border-b pb-2">Research Objectives</h2>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                        <li>To investigate the role of AI-based recruitment methods across recruitment stages in Malaysia[cite: 72].</li>
                        <li>To investigate the role of human-based recruitment methods across recruitment stages in Malaysia[cite: 73].</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-8 border border-gray-100">
                    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4 border-b pb-2">Research Questions</h2>
                    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                        <li>Which recruitment stages are more suitable for AI-based recruitment methods in Malaysia? [cite: 75]</li>
                        <li>Which recruitment stages are more suitable for human-based recruitment methods in Malaysia? [cite: 76]</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-xl p-8 border border-blue-100">
                <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4">Scope & Significance</h2>
                <p class="mb-2"><strong>Scope:</strong> The study focuses on individuals currently involved in recruitment and selection activities in Malaysia within organizations that have an internal HR department[cite: 104, 110].</p>
                <p><strong>Significance:</strong> It provides a stage-based understanding of AI and human involvement in recruitment, offering practical guidance for Malaysian organizations to maintain ethical standards and efficiency[cite: 165, 167].</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="literature" class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-8 border border-gray-100">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4 border-b pb-2">Literature Review & Framework</h2>
            <p class="mb-4"><strong>Underpinning Theories:</strong> The study is grounded in Sociotechnical Systems (STS) Theory, which views technology as part of a wider organizational context, and Human-AI Complementarity, which highlights that humans and AI achieve better outcomes when combined[cite: 195, 207, 215].</p>
            
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-800 mt-6 mb-2">Study Variables</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-6">
                <li><strong>Independent Variable 1:</strong> Recruitment Methods (AI-based and Human-based)[cite: 35, 298].</li>
                <li><strong>Independent Variable 2:</strong> Recruitment Stages (Job analysis, Sourcing, Screening, Assessment, Interview, Onboarding)[cite: 36, 86].</li>
                <li><strong>Dependent Variable:</strong> Level of AI and human involvement across recruitment stages[cite: 35].</li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-800 mt-6 mb-2">Hypotheses Summary</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li><strong>H1:</strong> Human methods have higher involvement in identifying needs/job analysis[cite: 78].</li>
                <li><strong>H2:</strong> AI methods have higher involvement in sourcing and attraction[cite: 79].</li>
                <li><strong>H3:</strong> AI methods have higher involvement in screening and shortlisting[cite: 80].</li>
                <li><strong>H4:</strong> AI methods have higher involvement in the assessment stage[cite: 81].</li>
                <li><strong>H5:</strong> Human methods have higher involvement in the interview stage[cite: 82].</li>
                <li><strong>H6:</strong> Human methods have higher involvement in induction and onboarding[cite: 83].</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="methodology" class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm p-8 border border-gray-100">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4 border-b pb-2">Research Methodology</h2>
            
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mt-6">
                <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-800">Research Design</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 mt-1">Quantitative, cross-sectional design evaluating comparison-based hypotheses[cite: 388, 392, 396].</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-800">Population & Sampling</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 mt-1">At least 100 HR practitioners in Malaysia, selected via purposive, convenience, and snowball sampling[cite: 409, 416].</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-800">Measurement</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 mt-1">Self-administered online questionnaire utilizing a 5-point involvement scale (1 = Very Low to 5 = Very High)[cite: 471, 555].</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-800">Data Analysis</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 mt-1">IBM SPSS Statistics for demographic and mean comparison analysis, and SmartPLS for measurement model validation (PLS-SEM)[cite: 578, 579, 583].</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

